NEW = [
  {"id":"fqa-swords-017","category":"swords","difficulty":"expert","question":"How does the nie-deki vs nioi-deki distinction inform school attribution?","answer":"Nie-deki and nioi-deki describe the dominant particle structure in the hamon and jihada, serving as primary school attribution markers. Nie consists of individually visible martensite particles appearing as bright points, characteristic of Soshu-den (Kamakura-era Sagami Province). Nioi-deki features particles too fine to distinguish individually, creating a misty effect along the hamon, typical of Bizen-den. Yamato-den tends toward nie, while Yamashiro-den shows balanced nie-nioi (ko-nie). Mino-den typically shows togari-ba (pointed) patterns in nioi-deki. These distinctions arise from differences in steel carbon content, quenching temperature, and clay application thickness during yakiire. A blade showing strong nie with itame-hada and notare-midare hamon points to Soshu tradition, while nioi-deki with mokume-hada and choji-midare suggests Bizen. However, later smiths deliberately combined elements across traditions.","evidence":["Honma Junji, Nihonto no Kantei","NBTHK educational materials"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["nie","nioi","school-attribution","metallurgy"]},
  {"id":"fqa-swords-018","category":"swords","difficulty":"expert","question":"What role does utsuri play in authenticating Bizen tradition blades?","answer":"Utsuri is a shadow-like reflection of the hamon visible in the ji (flat surface) of the blade, appearing as a whitish cloud pattern. It is considered one of the most difficult features to forge and serves as strong evidence of Bizen-den manufacture. Bo-utsuri (diffuse) appears in Ko-Bizen and early Kamakura works. Midare-utsuri (irregular) is characteristic of Kamakura-era Osafune smiths like Nagamitsu and Kagemitsu. Jifu-utsuri shows as scattered patches. The mechanism involves partial transformation of the steel during differential hardening — the clay application creates temperature gradients producing this secondary pattern. Modern smiths find utsuri extremely difficult to replicate, and its presence in a blade claiming pre-Muromachi Bizen origin provides significant authentication support. Its absence does not disprove authenticity, as it can be lost through excessive polishing.","evidence":["Sato Kanzan, The Japanese Sword","NBTHK kantei lectures"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["utsuri","bizen","authentication","metallurgy"]},
  {"id":"fqa-swords-019","category":"swords","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"Explain the significance of mei (signature) carving styles in dating and attribution.","answer":"Mei (inscribed signatures) on the nakago provide critical attribution evidence through multiple dimensions. Character style (kaisho vs gyosho vs sosho) varies by period and school. Stroke order and chisel technique are individual to each smith. Niji-mei (two-character) signatures predominate in Kamakura, while longer signatures with titles and dates become common in Muromachi. The position of mei on the nakago changes — tachi-mei appears on the side facing outward when worn edge-down, while katana-mei faces outward when worn edge-up, reflecting the shift from tachi to katana carrying convention around 1400. Gimei (false signatures) of famous smiths are common and require comparison with published oshigata (sword rubbing) collections. NBTHK maintains extensive oshigata databases for comparison. The chisel angle, stroke width, and character spacing are as individual as handwriting.","evidence":["Honma & Sato, Nihonto Meikan","NBTHK oshigata collections"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["mei","signature","dating","attribution"]},
  {"id":"fqa-swords-020","category":"swords","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"How do kissaki (point) shapes inform period attribution?","answer":"Kissaki shapes evolved systematically across periods, making them reliable dating indicators. Ko-kissaki (small point) characterizes Heian and early Kamakura blades, typically under 3cm. Chu-kissaki (medium point) becomes standard in mid-Kamakura, proportional to blade width. O-kissaki (large point) appears in late Kamakura Soshu-den blades, reflecting increased combat requirements during Mongol invasions. Ikubi-kissaki (stubby point) is specific to certain Kamakura-era works. The yokote line (boundary between ji and kissaki) should be clearly defined in quality blades. Boshi (temper pattern in the kissaki) provides additional attribution evidence — ko-maru (small round) turnback is common in Bizen, while the pointed Soshu-style boshi reflects that tradition. Alterations to kissaki shape through re-tempering or reshaping can indicate later modifications and affect both attribution and value.","evidence":["Fuller & Gregory, Japanese Art Swords","NBTHK study materials"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["kissaki","point-shape","period-dating","morphology"]},
  {"id":"fqa-ceramics-015","category":"ceramics","difficulty":"expert","question":"How does thermoluminescence (TL) dating work for Japanese ceramics authentication?","answer":"TL dating measures the accumulated radiation dose in crystalline minerals within the ceramic body since its last firing. When a ceramic is fired above 500°C, its TL signal is reset to zero. Over time, natural radiation from the clay's uranium, thorium, and potassium-40 content causes electrons to become trapped in crystal lattice defects. When heated in a laboratory, these trapped electrons are released as light (thermoluminescence), and the intensity is proportional to the time since last firing. For Japanese ceramics, TL dating is particularly valuable for pieces claiming Momoyama or earlier origin. The technique has accuracy of approximately ±15-20% for well-characterized samples. Limitations include sensitivity to previous heating events (e.g., fire damage), heterogeneous dose rates in the burial environment, and the requirement for a sample (typically from the base, ~100mg). TL is most powerful for rejecting fakes — a piece claiming 16th century origin but showing a TL date of 50 years is definitively modern.","evidence":["Oxford Authentication Ltd technical papers","JAEA (Japan Atomic Energy Agency) dating studies"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["TL-dating","scientific-analysis","authentication","ceramics-science"]},
  {"id":"fqa-ceramics-016","category":"ceramics","difficulty":"expert","question":"Describe the key differences between Ko-Seto and later Seto revival wares.","answer":"Ko-Seto (Old Seto) represents the only medieval Japanese stoneware tradition producing glazed wares, active from the late Kamakura through Muromachi periods (13th-16th centuries). Authentic Ko-Seto pieces show ash glaze with characteristic yellow-green to olive coloration from wood ash rich in calcium and potassium. The clay body is gray stoneware with visible sand particles. Forms include tenmoku tea bowls, vases, incense burners, and Buddhist ritual vessels. Kiln furniture marks on the base indicate tunnel kiln (anagama) firing. Later Seto revival wares (19th-20th century) differ in several key ways: clay body is often lighter colored from different clay sources; glazes use modern formulations producing more uniform color; forms may copy Ko-Seto shapes but lack the subtle asymmetry of medieval wheel work; and firing marks differ as later kilns used different stacking methods. XRF analysis of glaze composition can distinguish medieval from modern Seto production.","evidence":["Aichi Prefectural Ceramic Museum research","Seto City Archaeological Survey reports"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["ko-seto","seto","medieval-ceramics","glaze-analysis"]},
  {"id":"fqa-ceramics-017","category":"ceramics","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"What is kintsugi and how does it affect authentication and value?","answer":"Kintsugi (golden joinery) is the Japanese practice of repairing broken ceramics with urushi lacquer mixed with or dusted with gold powder. Rather than concealing damage, kintsugi celebrates the repair as part of the object's history, reflecting the wabi-sabi aesthetic. For authentication, kintsugi provides several forensic indicators: the age of the lacquer can be estimated through UV fluorescence and chemical analysis; the gold powder composition (pure gold vs alloy vs brass) indicates repair quality and approximate period; and the repair pattern reveals the original break, which itself may indicate genuine use versus staged damage. Period kintsugi (Momoyama-Edo) using genuine urushi and gold can actually increase a piece's value, especially if the repair itself has provenance. Modern kintsugi using epoxy and gold-colored materials is easily distinguished from traditional urushi-based repairs through UV examination. Some pieces have been deliberately broken and repaired with kintsugi to increase perceived value.","evidence":["Kyoto kintsugi workshops","Flickwerk: The Aesthetics of Mended Japanese Ceramics"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["kintsugi","repair","authentication","wabi-sabi"]},
  {"id":"fqa-ceramics-018","category":"ceramics","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"How does foot ring (kodai) analysis aid in ceramic authentication?","answer":"The foot ring is often called the most honest part of a ceramic piece because it reveals production methods difficult to fake. Key indicators include: clay color and texture visible where glaze was wiped away; trimming tool marks showing the potter's technique; kiln furniture adhesion marks indicating firing position; and wear patterns from use. For tea ceramics, specific foot ring types indicate tradition — the rough, irregular foot of a Hagi chawan versus the precise turned foot of a Nabeshima dish. Period-specific characteristics include the radial chattering marks from bamboo trimming tools in Ko-Seto, the deliberately rough 'kairagi' (crawling glaze) foot of certain Korean-inspired wares, and the precise geometric foot of Kakiemon porcelain. Forgers often succeed in replicating surface decoration but fail at foot ring details because these require understanding of the entire production process rather than just visual copying.","evidence":["Cort, Japanese Ceramics Technical Studies","Victoria and Albert Museum ceramic identification guides"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["foot-ring","kodai","authentication","production-technique"]},
  {"id":"fqa-ukiyoe-012","category":"ukiyoe","difficulty":"expert","question":"Explain the forensic significance of bokashi (color gradation) in print authentication.","answer":"Bokashi refers to the gradation technique where color fades from intense to light within a single printed area, achieved by wiping pigment from part of the block before printing. This technique is crucial for authentication because: it requires extreme skill from the printer (surishi), making each impression subtly unique; the moisture gradient on the paper creates characteristic fiber distortion visible under magnification; and the exact pattern of gradation is nearly impossible to replicate in photographic reproductions. In Hiroshige's landscape prints, bokashi creates the atmospheric effects (sky gradation, mist) that define the design's aesthetic. Early impressions show precise, controlled bokashi with clean transitions, while later impressions from fatigued printers show less refined gradations. Digital and photographic reproductions fail to replicate bokashi because the technique relies on physical pressure variation and moisture interaction with paper fibers, producing a three-dimensional quality that flat printing cannot achieve.","evidence":["Salter, Japanese Woodblock Printing","Keyes, Hiroshige's Tokaido printing analysis"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["bokashi","printing-technique","authentication","impression-quality"]},
  {"id":"fqa-ukiyoe-013","category":"ukiyoe","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"How do censor seals (kiwame-in, aratame-in) help date ukiyo-e prints?","answer":"Japanese woodblock prints bear censorship seals that provide precise dating evidence. The system evolved through several phases: Pre-1790, no systematic censorship. 1790-1842, kiwame seal (approved) used alone. 1842-1853, nanushi (town elder) seals paired with date seals following Tenpo reforms. 1853-1857, aratame (examined) seal introduced with date seals. 1858-1871, various combinations of aratame and date seals. Post-1872, censorship abolished. Each phase has documented seal formats that can be cross-referenced with known examples. Date seals indicate year and month using cyclical calendar. The presence of correct censor seals is necessary but not sufficient for authentication — high-quality reproductions may copy seal images. However, the seal impression depth, ink color, and position on the sheet provide supplementary authentication evidence. Some later reprints bear copied censor seals but these are typically printed rather than stamped, lacking the three-dimensional impression of genuine seals.","evidence":["Marks, Publishers of Japanese Woodblock Prints","Thompson, Censor Seals on Japanese Prints"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["censor-seals","dating","kiwame","aratame"]},
  {"id":"fqa-ukiyoe-014","category":"ukiyoe","difficulty":"expert","question":"What are the key indicators for identifying Meiji-era photomechanical reproductions of Edo prints?","answer":"Photomechanical reproductions of ukiyo-e began in the 1880s-90s using collotype, lithography, and later halftone processes. Key identification methods: Under magnification, photomechanical reproductions show dot patterns (halftone) or continuous tone without the characteristic wood grain texture of genuine woodblock prints. Paper analysis reveals machine-made paper with uniform fiber distribution versus handmade kozo paper with random fibers. Color analysis shows synthetic aniline dyes producing different spectral signatures from traditional pigments. Registration marks or crop marks may be visible at sheet edges. The embossing (karazuri) technique — blind printing creating texture without color — is absent in photomechanical reproductions because it requires physical block pressure. Back-of-sheet examination shows that genuine woodblock ink penetrates the paper in characteristic patterns, while lithographic and collotype inks sit primarily on the surface. Some Meiji publishers produced both genuine new woodblock editions and photomechanical reproductions, requiring careful analysis to distinguish.","evidence":["Brown, Block Printing and Book Illustration in Japan","Merritt, Woodblock Print Reproductions"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["photomechanical","reproduction","meiji","authentication"]},
  {"id":"fqa-ukiyoe-015","category":"ukiyoe","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"How does paper worm damage (mushikui) provide authentication evidence?","answer":"Paper worm damage (mushikui) creates characteristic small, irregular holes in paper that can serve as authentication evidence. Genuine worm damage shows: irregular channel patterns following the worm's path between paper layers; damage that penetrates multiple layers when prints were stored stacked; edges of holes showing natural fiber fraying; and brown-stained margins around holes from worm excrement. As authentication evidence, worm damage indicates the paper has been in a Japanese storage environment (typically in paulownia boxes) for extended periods. The pattern of damage — affecting the sheet margins more than the central image — is consistent with storage in folded or stacked formats. Fake worm damage, created by pin pricks or acid drops, shows too-regular hole patterns, clean edges without fiber fraying, and no associated staining. While worm damage alone cannot authenticate a print, its presence is consistent with age claims and its pattern can corroborate storage history.","evidence":["Paper conservation literature","International Ukiyo-e Society authentication seminars"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["mushikui","worm-damage","paper-analysis","storage-history"]},
  {"id":"fqa-painting-012","category":"painting","difficulty":"expert","question":"How does X-ray fluorescence (XRF) analysis distinguish period pigments in Japanese paintings?","answer":"XRF identifies elemental composition of pigments non-destructively. For Japanese paintings, key elemental signatures include: Lead (Pb) from lead white (enpaku) — used from ancient times but composition varies by period. Mercury (Hg) from vermillion/cinnabar (shu) — natural cinnabar shows trace elements absent in synthetic vermillion (post-1820s). Copper (Cu) from malachite green (rokusho) and azurite blue (gunjo) — particle size distribution differs between natural and synthetic. Arsenic (As) from orpiment yellow (sekio) — replaced by chrome yellow (Cr) in Meiji. Cobalt (Co) from smalt — introduced through Dutch trade in 18th century. Titanium (Ti) from titanium white — invented 1920s, definitive modern indicator. Chromium (Cr) from chrome green/yellow — definitive post-1800 indicator. The presence of titanium or chromium in a painting claiming Edo-period origin is conclusive evidence of modern materials. XRF mapping can also reveal pentimenti (hidden earlier compositions) that support authenticity through evidence of artistic process.","evidence":["Getty Conservation Institute XRF protocols","Tokyo National Research Institute for Cultural Properties"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["XRF","pigment-analysis","scientific-authentication","non-destructive"]},
  {"id":"fqa-painting-013","category":"painting","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"What is the significance of mounting (hyogu) in Japanese scroll painting authentication?","answer":"The mounting (hyogu) of a Japanese scroll painting provides significant authentication evidence beyond the painting itself. Period mountings use specific silk brocade patterns (kinran, donsu) that can be dated through textile analysis. The mounting format — hanging scroll (kakejiku), handscroll (emaki), or album leaf (gajo) — should be appropriate for the painting's claimed period and function. The ura-uchi (backing paper) layers show aging consistent with the mounting's claimed date. Roller ends (jiku) materials — bone, ivory, ceramic, or lacquered wood — indicate quality level and period. Historic remountings are documented by skilled hyogu-shi (mounters) who may add inscriptions noting the date and reason for remounting. Authentication red flags include: modern mounting materials on supposedly ancient paintings; mounting significantly newer than the painting without remounting documentation; and mounting format inappropriate for the painting's claimed context (e.g., tea ceremony scroll mounted in a non-tea format). The mounting itself can be more valuable than a minor painting if by a famous hyogu-shi.","evidence":["Kyoto National Museum mounting conservation studies","Hayakawa, The Art of Japanese Scroll Mounting"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["hyogu","mounting","scroll","authentication"]},
  {"id":"fqa-painting-014","category":"painting","difficulty":"expert","question":"How are infrared reflectography and imaging used in Japanese painting authentication?","answer":"Infrared (IR) reflectography penetrates pigment layers to reveal underdrawings (shita-e) and compositional changes invisible to the naked eye. In Japanese paintings, carbon-based ink (sumi) absorbs IR strongly, making preliminary brush sketches visible beneath mineral pigment layers. This is particularly valuable because: authentic works frequently show underdrawings revealing the artist's process — compositional adjustments, position changes, and corrections that demonstrate genuine creative work rather than copying; the underdrawing brush style can be compared to the artist's known calligraphic style; later additions or overpainting become visible as layers of different materials; and inscriptions hidden beneath later additions or repairs can be read. For Japanese paintings specifically, IR imaging can distinguish between sumi ink (carbon-based, IR-absorbing) and modern synthetic black inks. It can also reveal text or seals obscured by later mounting layers. The absence of any underdrawing in a supposedly major composition may indicate mechanical copying from a template rather than original composition.","evidence":["National Research Institute for Cultural Properties Tokyo","Kyoto National Museum IR imaging studies"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["infrared","reflectography","underdrawing","scientific-analysis"]},
]

